<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1916-01-21T23:59:59-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1916-01-21T00:00:00-05:00" n="783" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d783">
                            <note rend="inline" type="source">File No. 300.115/6737</note>
                            <head>
                                <hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in France</hi> (<persName corresp="#p_SWG1" type="from"><hi rend="italic">Sharp</hi></persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of State</gloss>
                                </hi>
                            </head>
                            <opener>
                                <seg rendition="#center">[Telegram]</seg>
                            </opener>
                            <opener>
                                <dateline rendition="#right">
                                    <placeName>
                                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Paris</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1916-01-21">
                                        <hi rend="italic">January 21, 1916</hi>
                                    </date>.<lb/>[<hi rend="italic">Received 9.45 p.
                                    m.</hi>]</dateline>
                            </opener>
                            <p>1230. Your 1298, 5th. Foreign Office replies that it is not possible
                                to grant a general authorization for the free exportation of hops as
                                requested, adding that hops of a similar quality can, as a matter of
                                fact, be found in Russia and in France and it does not appear that
                                the brewery industry of the United States depends on hops of German
                                and Austrian origin.</p>
                            <closer>
                                <signed>
                                    <persName corresp="#p_SWG1">
                                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Sharp</hi>
                                    </persName>
                                </signed>
                            </closer>
                        </div>
                        </body></text></TEI>